the night that she was born.

36:54.800 --> 36:57.640
How could a song have so much power?

36:58.440 --> 36:59.960
And power like him?

36:59.960 --> 37:01.840
- Like who?
- The oldest one.

37:01.840 --> 37:05.360
On the night of her birth,
he can't have been there.

37:05.360 --> 37:07.520
- What for?

37:08.080 --> 37:11.280
- What for? What for? What for?
Who was there?

37:15.360 --> 37:17.240
Enough.

37:18.320 --> 37:21.920
- Whoa!

37:21.920 --> 37:23.200
- You okay?
- Yeah, yeah.

37:23.200 --> 37:25.320
- I've got you. I've got you.
- Okay, okay.

37:25.320 --> 37:29.000
What was it? What happened?
- It's all right. All right? It's okay.

37:30.120 --> 37:33.320
This creature is very wrong.

37:33.320 --> 37:39.720
And this-- this is very, very, very right.

37:41.560 --> 37:43.280
Do you know what this is?

37:44.480 --> 37:46.720
This is the famous Abbey Road piano.

37:48.280 --> 37:51.320
They call it the Mrs Mills Piano.

37:51.320 --> 37:52.800
Oho!

37:52.800 --> 37:53.880
Oh, she was a girl.

37:53.880 --> 37:57.080
We had some adventures, me and Mrs Mills.

37:57.080 --> 38:01.200
But this is the piano that The Beatles
will play on their greatest hits.

38:01.720 --> 38:02.840
"Penny Lane".

38:02.840 --> 38:05.280
"Lady Madonna". All from this.

38:06.240 --> 38:08.320
So I know that this piano is rattling

38:08.320 --> 38:11.320
